default3.1
default              
defaultLocal Transport Authorities (LTAs) do have the capacity to deliver local transport schemes
default as demonstrated by the delivery of projects under the previous f
defaultunding arrangements, i.e. once 
defaultlocal 
defaultmajor scheme funding had been secured from central Government. The most recent example from 
defaultKent
default was the completion of the East Kent Access (EKA) road
default, an £87m scheme delivered by Kent County Council on time and to budg
defaultet. 
defaultLTAs also have the capacity to assess and prioritise local transport schemes as
default demons
defaulttrated by the work that is being
default 
defaultdone by local authorities for the prioritisation and assessment of transport schemes being funded through Local Transport Body (LTB) 
defaultdevolved funding
default;
default and the prioritisation work currently underway for the new single Local Growth Fund (LGF)
default devolved to Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs)
default post 2015.
default  
default&#xa0;
default3.2
default              
defaultThe LTB and the 
defaultLEP
default, as bodies in their own right, do not have the capacity to assess, prioritise or deliver local transport schemes. The LTB and the LEP do not have the staff resources to complete such detailed and technical tasks and ultimately the work comes back to the l
defaultocal authorities that make up the LTB and the LEP. This is at a time when local authority resources are under intense budgetary pressure. Alternatively, additional project costs are incurred through outsourcing work to external consultants. The private sec
defaulttor organisations involved with the LEP also do not have the capacity or expertise to complete transport scheme appraisal and prioritisation. 
